# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ultrasonic-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Echo sounding can also be used for ranging to other targets, such as fish schools.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Hydroacoustic assessments have traditionally employed mobile surveys from boats to evaluate fish biomass and spatial distributions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Conversely, fixed-location techniques use stationary transducers to monitor passing fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The word *sounding* is used for all types of depth measurements, including those that don't use sound, and is unrelated in origin to the word *sound* in the sense of noise or tones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Echo sounding is a more rapid method of measuring depth than the previous technique of lowering a sounding line until it touched bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] German inventor Alexander Behm was granted German patent No.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] 282009 for the invention of echo sounding *(device for measuring depths of the sea and distances and headings of ships or obstacles by means of reflected sound waves)* on 22 July 1913.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] His work was developed and implemented by other scientists and technicians such as Chilowski, Florisson and Pierre Marti.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Though a fully operational *échosondeur* (sonar) was not ready for use in wartime, there were successful trials both off Toulon and in the English Channel as early as 1920, and French patents taken for civilian uses.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Oceanographic ships and French high-sea fishing assistance vessels were equipped with Langevin-Florisson and Langevin Marti recording sonars as early as the mid/late 1920s.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] One of the first commercial echo sounding units was the Fessenden Fathometer, which used the Fessenden oscillator to generate sound waves.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] This was first installed by the Submarine Signal Company in 1924 on the M&M liner SS Berkshire.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Distance is measured by multiplying half the time from the signal's outgoing pulse to its return by the speed of sound in water, which is approximately 1.5 kilometres per second.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The speed of sound will vary slightly depending on temperature, pressure and salinity; and for precise applications of echosounding, such as hydrography, the speed of sound must also be measured, typically by deploying a sound velocity probe in the water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Echo sounding is a special purpose application of sonar used to locate the bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Since a historical pre-SI unit of water depth was the fathom, an instrument used for determining water depth is sometimes called a **fathometer**.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Most charted ocean depths are based on an average or standard sound speed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Where greater accuracy is required, average and even seasonal standards may be applied to ocean regions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] For high accuracy depths, usually restricted to special purpose or scientific surveys, a sensor may be lowered to measure the temperature, pressure and salinity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] These factors are used to estimate more accurately the actual sound speed in the local water column.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] This technique is often used by the US Office of Coast Survey for navigational surveys of US coastal waters.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] A single-beam echo sounder is one of the simplest and most fundamental types of underwater sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] They are ubiquitous in the boating world and used on a number of different marine robotic vehicles.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] It operates by using a transducer to emit a pulse through the water and listen for echoes to return.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Using that data, it's able to determine the distance from the strongest echo, which can be the seafloor, a concrete structure, or other larger obstacle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] A fishfinder is an echo sounding device used by both recreational and commercial fishers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] A multibeam echosounder (MBES) is a type of sonar that is used to map the seabed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] It emits acoustic waves in a fan shape beneath its transceiver.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The time it takes for the sound waves to reflect off the seabed and return to the receiver is used to calculate the water depth.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Unlike other sonars and echo sounders, MBES uses beamforming to extract directional information from the returning soundwaves, producing a swathe of depth soundings from a single ping.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] As well as an aid to navigation (most larger vessels will have at least a simple depth sounder), echo sounding is commonly used for fishing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Variations in elevation often represent places where fish congregate.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] In areas where detailed bathymetry is required, a precise echo sounder may be used for the work of hydrography.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] There are many considerations when evaluating such a system, not limited to the vertical accuracy, resolution, acoustic beamwidth of the transmit/receive beam and the acoustic frequency of the transducer.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The majority of hydrographic echosounders are dual frequency, meaning that a low frequency pulse (typically around 24 kHz) can be transmitted at the same time as a high frequency pulse (typically around 200 kHz).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] As the two frequencies are discrete, the two return signals do not typically interfere with each other.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Dual frequency echosounding has many advantages, including the ability to identify a vegetation layer or a layer of soft mud on top of a layer of rock.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Most hydrographic operations use a 200 kHz transducer, which is suitable for inshore work up to 100 metres in depth.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Deeper water requires a lower frequency transducer as the acoustic signal of lower frequencies is less susceptible to attenuation in the water column.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Commonly used frequencies for deep water sounding are 33 kHz and 24 kHz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The beamwidth of the transducer is also a consideration for the hydrographer, as to obtain the best resolution of the data gathered a narrow beamwidth is preferable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The higher the operating frequency, the narrower the beamwidth.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Therefore, it is especially important when sounding in deep water, as the resulting footprint of the acoustic pulse can be very large once it reaches a distant sea floor.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] These systems are detailed further in the section called multibeam echosounder.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Echo sounders are used in laboratory applications to monitor sediment transport, scour and erosion processes in scale models (hydraulic models, flumes etc.).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] These can also be used to create plots of 3D contours.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] The required precision and accuracy of the hydrographic echo sounder is defined by the requirements of the International Hydrographic Organization (IHO) for surveys that are to be undertaken to IHO standards.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] These values are contained within IHO publication S44.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] In order to meet these standards, the surveyor must consider not only the vertical and horizontal accuracy of the echo sounder and transducer, but the survey system as a whole.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] A motion sensor may be used, specifically the heave component (in single beam echosounding) to reduce soundings for the motion of the vessel experienced on the water's surface.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Once all of the uncertainties of each sensor are established, the hydrographer will create an uncertainty budget to determine whether the survey system meets the requirements laid down by IHO.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Different hydrographic organisations will have their own set of field procedures and manuals to guide their surveyors to meet the required standards.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/echo-sounding] Two examples are the US Army Corps of Engineers publication EM110-2-1003, and the NOAA 'Field Procedures Manual'.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect results from the linear electromechanical interaction between the mechanical and electrical states in crystalline materials with no inversion symmetry.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect is a reversible process: materials exhibiting the piezoelectric effect also exhibit the reverse piezoelectric effect, the internal generation of a mechanical strain resulting from an applied electric field.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For example, lead zirconate titanate crystals will generate measurable piezoelectricity when their static structure is deformed by about 0.1% of the original dimension.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Conversely, those same crystals will change about 0.1% of their static dimension when an external electric field is applied.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The inverse piezoelectric effect is used in the production of ultrasound waves.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] French physicists Jacques and Pierre Curie discovered piezoelectricity in 1880.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] It forms the basis for scanning probe microscopes that resolve images at the scale of atoms.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] It is used in the pickups of some electronically amplified guitars and as triggers in most modern electronic drums.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect also finds everyday uses, such as generating sparks to ignite gas cooking and heating devices, torches, and cigarette lighters.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The word *piezoelectricity* means electricity resulting from pressure.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] It is derived from Ancient Greek πιέζω*(*piézō*)* 'to squeeze or press' and ἤλεκτρον*(*ḗlektron*)* 'amber' (an ancient source of static electricity).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The German form of the word (*Piezoelektrizität*) was coined in 1881 by the German physicist Wilhelm Gottlieb Hankel; the English word was derived from German in 1883.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The pyroelectric effect, by which a material generates an electric potential in response to a temperature change, was studied by Carl Linnaeus and Franz Aepinus in the mid-18th century.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Drawing on this knowledge, both René Just Haüy and Antoine César Becquerel posited a relationship between mechanical stress and electric charge; however, experiments by both proved inconclusive.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The first demonstration of the direct piezoelectric effect was in 1880 by the brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Quartz and Rochelle salt exhibited the most piezoelectricity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The Curies, however, did not predict the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The converse effect was mathematically deduced from fundamental thermodynamic principles by Gabriel Lippmann in 1881.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The Curies immediately confirmed the existence of the converse effect, and went on to obtain quantitative proof of the complete reversibility of electro-elasto-mechanical deformations in piezoelectric crystals.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For the next few decades, piezoelectricity remained something of a laboratory curiosity, though it was a vital tool in the discovery of polonium and radium by Pierre and Marie Curie in 1898.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] More work was done to explore and define the crystal structures that exhibited piezoelectricity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This culminated in 1910 with the publication of Woldemar Voigt's *Lehrbuch der Kristallphysik* (*Textbook on Crystal Physics*), which described the 20 natural crystal classes capable of piezoelectricity, and rigorously defined the piezoelectric constants using tensor analysis.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The first practical application for piezoelectric devices was sonar, first developed during World War I.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The superior performance of piezoelectric devices, operating at ultrasonic frequencies, superseded the earlier Fessenden oscillator.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In France in 1917, Paul Langevin and his coworkers developed an ultrasonic submarine detector.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The detector consisted of a transducer, made of thin quartz crystals carefully glued between two steel plates, and a hydrophone to detect the returned echo.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] By emitting a high-frequency pulse from the transducer, and measuring the amount of time it takes to hear an echo from the sound waves bouncing off an object, one can calculate the distance to that object.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric devices found homes in many fields.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ceramic phonograph cartridges simplified player design, were cheap and accurate, and made record players cheaper to maintain and easier to build.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The development of the ultrasonic transducer allowed for easy measurement of viscosity and elasticity in fluids and solids, resulting in huge advances in materials research.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic time-domain reflectometers (which send an ultrasonic pulse through a material and measure reflections from discontinuities) could find flaws inside cast metal and stone objects, improving structural safety.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] During World War II, independent research groups in the United States, USSR, and Japan discovered a new class of synthetic materials, called ferroelectrics, which exhibited piezoelectric constants many times higher than natural materials.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This led to intense research to develop barium titanate and later lead zirconate titanate materials with specific properties for particular applications.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] One significant example of the use of piezoelectric crystals was developed by Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Lack, working in radio telephony in the engineering department, developed the "AT cut" crystal, a crystal that operated through a wide range of temperatures.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Lack's crystal did not need the heavy accessories previous crystal used, facilitating its use on the aircraft.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This development allowed Allied air forces to engage in coordinated mass attacks through the use of aviation radio.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Development of piezoelectric devices and materials in the United States was kept within the companies doing the development, mostly due to the wartime beginnings of the field, and in the interests of securing profitable patents.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] New materials were the first to be developed—quartz crystals were the first commercially exploited piezoelectric material, but scientists searched for higher-performance materials.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Despite the advances in materials and the maturation of manufacturing processes, the United States market did not grow as quickly as Japan's did.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Without many new applications, the growth of the United States' piezoelectric industry suffered.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In contrast, Japanese manufacturers shared their information, quickly overcoming technical and manufacturing challenges and creating new markets.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In Japan, a temperature stable crystal cut was developed by Issac Koga.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Japanese efforts in materials research created piezoceramic materials competitive to the United States materials but free of expensive patent restrictions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers that transmit sound waves through air had existed for quite some time but first saw major commercial use in early television remote controls.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] These transducers now are mounted on several car models as an echolocation device, helping the driver determine the distance from the car to any objects that may be in its path.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The nature of the piezoelectric effect is closely related to the occurrence of electric dipole moments in solids.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] These may be either induced for ions on crystal lattice sites with asymmetric charge surroundings (as in BaTiO3 and PZTs) or directly carried by molecular groups (as in cane sugar).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The dipole density or polarization (dimensionality [C·m/m3] ) may easily be calculated for crystals by summing up the dipole moments per volume of the crystallographic unit cell.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] As every dipole is a vector, the dipole density ***P*** is a vector field.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Dipoles near each other tend to be aligned in regions called Weiss domains.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The domains are usually randomly oriented, but can be aligned using the process of *poling* (not the same as magnetic poling), a process by which a strong electric field is applied across the material, usually at elevated temperatures.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Not all piezoelectric materials can be poled.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Of importance for the piezoelectric effect is the change of polarization ***P*** when applying a mechanical stress.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This might either be caused by a reconfiguration of the dipole-inducing surrounding or by re-orientation of molecular dipole moments under the influence of the external stress.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectricity may then manifest in a variation of the polarization strength, its direction or both, with the details depending on: 1. the orientation of ***P*** within the crystal; 2. crystal symmetry; and 3. the applied mechanical stress.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The change in ***P*** appears as a variation of surface charge density upon the crystal faces, i.e. as a variation of the electric field extending between the faces caused by a change in dipole density in the bulk.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For example, a 1 cm3 cube of quartz with 2 kN (500 lbf) of correctly applied force can produce a voltage of 12500 V.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric materials also show the opposite effect, called the **converse piezoelectric effect**, where the application of an electrical field creates mechanical deformation in the crystal.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] where ${\mathfrak {d}}$ is the piezoelectric tensor and the superscript t stands for its transpose.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] where [*d*] is the matrix for the direct piezoelectric effect and [*d*t] is the matrix for the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The superscript *E* indicates a zero, or constant, electric field; the superscript *T* indicates a zero, or constant, stress field; and the superscript t stands for transposition of a matrix.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Notice that the third order tensor ${\mathfrak {d}}$ maps vectors into symmetric matrices.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] There are no non-trivial rotation-invariant tensors that have this property, which is why there are no isotropic piezoelectric materials.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] where the first equation represents the relationship for the converse piezoelectric effect and the latter for the direct piezoelectric effect.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Although the above equations are the most used form in literature, some comments about the notation are necessary.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Generally, *D* and *E* are vectors, that is, Cartesian tensors of rank 1; and permittivity *ε* is a Cartesian tensor of rank 2.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Strain and stress are, in principle, also rank-2 tensors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] But conventionally, because strain and stress are all symmetric tensors, the subscript of strain and stress can be relabeled in the following fashion: 11 → 1; 22 → 2; 33 → 3; 23 → 4; 13 → 5; 12 → 6.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] (Different conventions may be used by different authors in literature.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For example, some use 12 → 4; 23 → 5; 31 → 6 instead.) That is why *S* and *T* appear to have the "vector form" of six components.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Consequently, *s* appears to be a 6-by-6 matrix instead of a rank-3 tensor.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Such a relabeled notation is often called Voigt notation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Whether the shear strain components *S*4, *S*5, *S*6 are tensor components or engineering strains is another question.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In the equation above, they must be engineering strains for the 6,6 coefficient of the compliance matrix to be written as shown, i.e., 2(*s**E* 11 − *s**E* 12).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Engineering shear strains are double the value of the corresponding tensor shear, such as *S*6 = 2*S*12 and so on.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This also means that *s*66 = ⁠1/*G*12⁠, where *G*12 is the shear modulus.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] where the first set of four terms corresponds to the direct piezoelectric effect and the second set of four terms corresponds to the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The equality between the direct piezoelectric tensor and the transpose of the converse piezoelectric tensor originates from the Maxwell relations of thermodynamics.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For those piezoelectric crystals for which the polarization is of the crystal-field induced type, a formalism has been worked out that allows for the calculation of piezoelectrical coefficients *dij* from electrostatic lattice constants or higher-order Madelung constants.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Of the 32 crystal classes, 21 are non-centrosymmetric (not having a centre of symmetry), and of these, 20 exhibit direct piezoelectricity (the 21st is the cubic class 432).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ten of these represent the polar crystal classes, which show a spontaneous polarization without mechanical stress due to a non-vanishing electric dipole moment associated with their unit cell, and which exhibit pyroelectricity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] If the dipole moment can be reversed by applying an external electric field, the material is said to be ferroelectric.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For polar crystals, for which ***P*** ≠ 0 holds without applying a mechanical load, the piezoelectric effect manifests itself by changing the magnitude or the direction of ***P*** or both.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For the nonpolar but piezoelectric crystals, on the other hand, a polarization ***P*** different from zero is only elicited by applying a mechanical load.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For them the stress can be imagined to transform the material from a nonpolar crystal class (***P*** = 0) to a polar one, having ***P*** ≠ 0.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Many materials exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ceramics with randomly oriented grains must be ferroelectric to exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Macroscopic piezoelectricity is possible in textured polycrystalline non-ferroelectric piezoelectric materials, such as AlN and ZnO.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The fabrication of lead-free piezoceramics pose multiple challenges, from an environmental standpoint and their ability to replicate the properties of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] By removing the lead component of the piezoceramic, the risk of toxicity to humans decreases, but the mining and extraction of the materials can be harmful to the environment.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Most of the concerns with KNN, specifically its Nb2O5 component, are in the early phase of its life cycle before it reaches manufacturers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Since the harmful impacts are focused on these early phases, some actions can be taken to minimize the effects.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Returning the land as close to its original form after Nb2O5 mining via dam deconstruction or replacing a stockpile of utilizable soil are known aids for any extraction event.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For minimizing air quality effects, modeling and simulation still needs to occur to fully understand what mitigation methods are required.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The extraction of lead-free piezoceramic components has not grown to a significant scale at this time, but from early analysis, experts encourage caution when it comes to environmental effects.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Fabricating lead-free piezoceramics faces the challenge of maintaining the performance and stability of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In general, the main fabrication challenge is creating the "morphotropic phase boundaries (MPBs)" that provide the materials with their stable piezoelectric properties without introducing the "polymorphic phase boundaries (PPBs)" that decrease the temperature stability of the material.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] New phase boundaries are created by varying additive concentrations so that the phase transition temperatures converge at room temperature.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The introduction of the MPB improves piezoelectric properties, but if a PPB is introduced, the material becomes negatively affected by temperature.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Research is ongoing to control the type of phase boundaries that are introduced through phase engineering, diffusing phase transitions, domain engineering, and chemical modification.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] A piezoelectric potential can be created in any bulk or nanostructured semiconductor crystal having non central symmetry, such as the Group III–V and II–VI materials, due to polarization of ions under applied stress and strain.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] This property is common to both the zincblende and wurtzite crystal structures.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] To first order, there is only one independent piezoelectric coefficient in zincblende, called e14, coupled to shear components of the strain.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In wurtzite, there are instead three independent piezoelectric coefficients: *e*31, *e*33 and *e*15.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The semiconductors where the strongest piezoelectricity is observed are those commonly found in the wurtzite structure, i.e.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] GaN, InN, AlN and ZnO (see piezotronics).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Since 2006, there have also been a number of reports of strong non linear piezoelectric effects in polar semiconductors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Such effects are generally recognized to be at least important if not of the same order of magnitude as the first order approximation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response of polymers is not as high as the response for ceramics; however, polymers hold properties that ceramics do not.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Over the last few decades, non-toxic, piezoelectric polymers have been studied and applied due to their flexibility and smaller acoustical impedance.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Other properties that make these materials significant include their biocompatibility, biodegradability, low cost, and low power consumption compared to other piezo-materials (ceramics, etc.).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric polymers can be classified by bulk polymers, voided charged polymers ("piezoelectrets"), and polymer composites.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] A piezo-response observed by bulk polymers is mostly due to its molecular structure.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] There are two types of bulk polymers: amorphous and semi-crystalline.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Examples of semi-crystalline polymers are polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) and its copolymers, polyamides, and parylene-C.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Non-crystalline polymers, such as polyimide and polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC), fall under amorphous bulk polymers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Voided charged polymers exhibit the piezoelectric effect due to charge induced by poling of a porous polymeric film.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Under an electric field, charges form on the surface of the voids forming dipoles.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Electric responses can be caused by any deformation of these voids.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect can also be observed in polymer composites by integrating piezoelectric ceramic particles into a polymer film.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] A polymer does not have to be piezo-active to be an effective material for a polymer composite.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In this case, a material could be made up of an inert matrix with a separate piezo-active component.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] PVDF exhibits piezoelectricity several times greater than quartz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response observed from PVDF is about 20–30 pC/N.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] That is an order of 5–50 times less than that of piezoelectric ceramic lead zirconate titanate (PZT).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The thermal stability of the piezoelectric effect of polymers in the PVDF family (i.e. vinylidene fluoride co-poly trifluoroethylene) goes up to 125 °C.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Some applications of PVDF are pressure sensors, hydrophones, and shock wave sensors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Due to their flexibility, piezoelectric composites have been proposed as energy harvesters and nanogenerators.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In 2018, it was reported by Zhu et al. that a piezoelectric response of about 17 pC/N could be obtained from PDMS/PZT nanocomposite at 60% porosity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Another PDMS nanocomposite was reported in 2017, in which BaTiO3 was integrated into PDMS to make a stretchable, transparent nanogenerator for self-powered physiological monitoring.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In 2016, polar molecules were introduced into a polyurethane foam in which high responses of up to 244 pC/N were reported.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Most materials exhibit at least weak piezoelectric responses.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Trivial examples include sucrose (table sugar), DNA, and viral proteins, including those from bacteriophage.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] An actuator based on wood fibers (cellulose fibers) has been reported.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] D33 responses for cellular polypropylene are around 200 pC/N.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Some applications of cellular polypropylene are musical key pads, microphones, and ultrasound-based echolocation systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Recently, a single amino acid, β-glycine, displayed a high piezoelectric response of 178 pm V−1 compared with other biological materials.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ionic liquids were recently identified as the first piezoelectric liquid.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Direct piezoelectricity of some substances, like quartz, can generate potential differences of thousands of volts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The principle of operation of a piezoelectric sensor is that a physical dimension, transformed into a force, acts on two opposing faces of the sensing element.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Depending on the design of a sensor, different "modes" to load the piezoelectric element can be used: longitudinal, transversal and shear.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Detection of pressure variations in the form of sound is the most common sensor application, e.g. piezoelectric microphones (sound waves bend the piezoelectric material, creating a changing voltage) and piezoelectric pickups for acoustic-electric guitars.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] A piezo sensor attached to the body of an instrument is known as a contact microphone.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric sensors especially are used with high frequency sound in ultrasonic transducers for medical imaging and also industrial nondestructive testing (NDT).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For many sensing techniques, the sensor can act as both a sensor and an actuator—often the term *transducer* is preferred when the device acts in this dual capacity, but most piezo devices have this property of reversibility whether it is used or not.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers, for example, can inject ultrasound waves into the body, receive the returned wave, and convert it to an electrical signal (a voltage).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Most medical ultrasound transducers are piezoelectric.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] As very high electric fields correspond to only tiny changes in the width of the crystal, this width can be changed with better-than-μm precision, making piezo crystals the most important tool for positioning objects with extreme accuracy—thus their use in actuators.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Multilayer ceramics, using layers thinner than 100 μm, allow reaching high electric fields with voltage lower than 150 V.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] These ceramics are used within two kinds of actuators: direct piezo actuators and amplified piezoelectric actuators.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] While direct actuator's stroke is generally lower than 100 μm, amplified piezo actuators can reach millimeter strokes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectrical properties of quartz are useful as a standard of frequency.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Aside from the stepping stick-slip motor, all these motors work on the same principle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Driven by dual orthogonal vibration modes with a phase difference of 90°, the contact point between two surfaces vibrates in an elliptical path, producing a frictional force between the surfaces.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Usually, one surface is fixed, causing the other to move.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In most piezoelectric motors, the piezoelectric crystal is excited by a sine wave signal at the resonant frequency of the motor.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Using the resonance effect, a much lower voltage can be used to produce a high vibration amplitude.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] A stick-slip motor works using the inertia of a mass and the friction of a clamp.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Some are used for camera sensor displacement, thus allowing an anti-shake function.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Different teams of researchers have been investigating ways to reduce vibrations in materials by attaching piezo elements to the material.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] When the material is bent by a vibration in one direction, the vibration-reduction system responds to the bend and sends electric power to the piezo element to bend in the other direction.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Applications to flexible structures, such as shells and plates, have also been studied for nearly three decades.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezosurgery is a minimally invasive technique that aims to cut a target tissue with little damage to neighboring tissues.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] For example, Hoigne *et al.* uses frequencies in the range 25–29 kHz, causing microvibrations of 60–210 μm.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] It has the ability to cut mineralized tissue without cutting neurovascular tissue and other soft tissue, thereby maintaining a blood-free operating area, better visibility and greater precision.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] In 2019, Pernas-Salomón and Shmuel developed a dynamic homogenization method by which they were the first to show that piezoelectric composites exhibit an effective coupling between linear momentum and the electric field, which they termed electro-momentum coupling.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Because homogeneous piezoelectric materials do not exhibit this coupling, such composites belong to the class of metamaterials—artificial media engineered to display extraordinary effective properties, in magnitude or in kind.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Electro-momentum coupling is analogous to Willis coupling in elastic composites, which couples linear momentum to strain and was discovered by J.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] The local part of these couplings—like piezoelectric coupling—emerges from broken symmetries.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric metamaterials with electro-momentum coupling offer a mechanism for wave manipulation akin to Willis coupling: they impart a direction-dependent phase shift that enables wavefront shaping, with the added advantage of electrical tunability.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] "Sonar" can refer to one of two types of technology: *passive* sonar means listening for the sound made by vessels; *active* sonar means emitting pulses of sounds and listening for echoes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sonar may be used as a means of acoustic location and of measurement of the echo characteristics of "targets" in the water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Acoustic location in air was used before the introduction of radar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sonar may also be used for robot navigation, and sodar (an upward-looking in-air sonar) is used for atmospheric investigations.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The term *sonar* is also used for the equipment used to generate and receive the sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The acoustic frequencies used in sonar systems vary from very low (infrasonic) to extremely high (ultrasonic).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The study of underwater sound is known as underwater acoustics or hydroacoustics.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The first recorded use of the technique was in 1490 by Leonardo da Vinci, who used a tube inserted into the water to detect vessels by ear.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It was developed during World War I to counter the growing threat of submarine warfare, with an operational passive sonar system in use by 1918.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Modern active sonar systems use an acoustic transducer to generate a sound wave which is reflected from target objects.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In the late 19th century, an underwater bell was used as an ancillary to lighthouses or lightships to provide warning of hazards.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The use of sound to "echo-locate" underwater in the same way as bats use sound for aerial navigation seems to have been prompted by the *Titanic* disaster of 1912.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The world's first patent for an underwater echo-ranging device was filed at the British Patent Office by English meteorologist Lewis Fry Richardson a month after the sinking of *Titanic*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A German physicist Alexander Behm obtained a patent for an echo sounder in 1913.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The Canadian engineer Reginald Fessenden, while working for the Submarine Signal Company in Boston, Massachusetts, built an experimental system beginning in 1912, a system later tested in Boston Harbor, and in 1914 from the U.S.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Revenue Cutter *Miami* on the Grand Banks off Newfoundland.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In that test, Fessenden demonstrated depth sounding, underwater communications (Morse code) and echo ranging, detecting an iceberg at a 2-mile (3.2 km) range.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The "Fessenden oscillator", operated at about 500 Hz frequency, was unable to determine the bearing of the iceberg due to the 3-metre wavelength and the small dimension of the transducer's radiating face, less than 1⁄3 wavelength in diameter.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1915, the ten Montreal-built British H-class submarines launched were equipped with Fessenden oscillators.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] During World War I the need to detect submarines prompted more research into the use of sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The British made early use of underwater listening devices called hydrophones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The French physicist Paul Langevin, working with a Russian immigrant electrical engineer Constantin Chilowsky, worked on the development of active sound devices for detecting submarines in 1915.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Although piezoelectric and magnetostrictive transducers later superseded the electrostatic transducers they used, this work influenced future designs.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Lightweight sound-sensitive plastic film and fibre optics have been used for hydrophones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Terfenol-D and lead magnesium niobate (PMN) have been developed for projectors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1916, under the British Board of Invention and Research, Canadian physicist Robert William Boyle took on the active sound detection project with A.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Wood, producing a prototype for testing in mid-1917.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This work for the Anti-Submarine Division of the British Naval Staff was undertaken in utmost secrecy, and used quartz piezoelectric crystals to produce the world's first practical underwater active sound detection apparatus.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To maintain secrecy, no mention of sound experimentation or quartz was made – the word used to describe the early work ("supersonics") was changed to "ASD"ics, and the quartz material to "ASD"ivite: "ASD" for "Anti-Submarine Division", hence the British acronym *ASDIC*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1939, in response to a question from the *Oxford English Dictionary*, the Admiralty made up the story that it stood for "Allied Submarine Detection Investigation Committee", and this is still widely believed, though no committee bearing this name has been found in the Admiralty archives.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] By 1918, Britain and France had built prototype active systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The British tested their ASDIC on HMS *Antrim* in 1920 and started production in 1922.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The 6th Destroyer Flotilla had ASDIC-equipped vessels in 1923.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An anti-submarine school HMS *Osprey* and a training flotilla of four vessels were established on Portland in 1924.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] By the outbreak of World War II, the Royal Navy had five sets for different surface ship classes, and others for submarines, incorporated into a complete anti-submarine system.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The effectiveness of early ASDIC was hampered by the use of the depth charge as an anti-submarine weapon.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This required an attacking vessel to pass over a submerged contact before dropping charges over the stern, resulting in a loss of ASDIC contact in the moments leading up to attack.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The hunter was effectively firing blind, during which time a submarine commander could take evasive action.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This situation was remedied with new tactics and new weapons.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The tactical improvements developed by Frederic John Walker included the creeping attack.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Two anti-submarine ships were needed for this, usually sloops or corvettes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] One, the "directing ship" tracked the target submarine on ASDIC, while the second ship, with her ASDIC turned off and running at 5 knots, started an attack as directed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The low speed of the approach meant the submarine could not predict when depth charges were going to be released.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Any evasive action was detected by the directing ship and steering orders to the attacking ship given accordingly.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The new weapons to deal with the ASDIC blind spot were "ahead-throwing weapons", such as Hedgehogs and later Squids, which projected warheads at a target ahead of the attacker and still in ASDIC contact.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] These allowed a single escort to make better aimed attacks on submarines.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Developments during the war resulted in British ASDIC sets that used several different shapes of beam, such as the Q attachment to the Type 144 set, which was aligned at a deeper angle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The Type 147B set, which had an articulated transducer, enabled operators to cover the blind spot.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Another development was the FIDO Homing Torpedo, which aimed itself at the target submarine using passive sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Early in World War II (September 1940), British ASDIC technology was transferred for free to the United States.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Research on ASDIC and underwater sound was expanded in the UK and in the US.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Many new types of military sound detection were developed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] These included sonobuoys, first developed by the British in 1944 under the codename *High Tea*, dipping/dunking sonar and mine-detection sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This work formed the basis for post-war developments related to countering the nuclear submarine.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] During the 1930s American engineers developed their own underwater sound-detection technology, and important discoveries were made, such as the existence of thermoclines and their effects on sound waves.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Americans began to use the term *SONAR* for their systems, coined by Frederick Hunt to be the equivalent of RADAR.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Warren Horton's services for the first time.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] On leave from Bell Labs, he served the government as a technical expert, first at the experimental station at Nahant, Massachusetts, and later at US Naval Headquarters, in London, England.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] At Nahant he applied the newly developed vacuum tube, then associated with the formative stages of the field of applied science now known as electronics, to the detection of underwater signals.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] As a result, the carbon button microphone, which had been used in earlier detection equipment, was replaced by the precursor of the modern hydrophone.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Also during this period, he experimented with methods for towing detection.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This was due to the increased sensitivity of his device.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The principles are still used in modern towed sonar systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To meet the defense needs of Great Britain, Horton was sent to England to install in the Irish Sea bottom-mounted hydrophones connected to a shore listening post by submarine cable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] While this equipment was being loaded on the cable-laying vessel, World War I ended and he returned home.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] During World War II, Horton continued to develop sonar systems that could detect submarines, mines, and torpedoes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] He published *Fundamentals of Sonar* in 1957 as chief research consultant at the US Navy Underwater Sound Laboratory.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] He held this position until 1959 when he became technical director, a position he held until mandatory retirement in 1963.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] There was little progress in US sonar from 1915 to 1940.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1940, US sonars typically consisted of a magnetostrictive transducer and an array of nickel tubes connected to a 1-foot-diameter steel plate attached back-to-back to a Rochelle salt crystal in a spherical housing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This assembly penetrated the ship hull and was manually rotated to the desired angle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The piezoelectric Rochelle salt crystal had better parameters, but the magnetostrictive unit was much more reliable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] High losses to US merchant supply shipping early in World War II led to large scale high priority US research in the field, pursuing both improvements in magnetostrictive transducer parameters and Rochelle salt reliability.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Ammonium dihydrogen phosphate (ADP), a superior alternative, was found as a replacement for Rochelle salt; the first application was a replacement of the 24 kHz Rochelle-salt transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Within nine months, Rochelle salt was obsolete.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The ADP manufacturing facility grew from few dozen personnel in early 1940 to several thousands in 1942.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] One of the earliest application of ADP crystals were hydrophones for acoustic mines.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The crystals were specified for low-frequency cutoff at 5 Hz, withstanding mechanical shock for deployment from aircraft from 3,000 m (10,000 ft), and ability to survive neighbouring mine explosions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] One of key features of ADP reliability is its zero aging characteristics; the crystal keeps its parameters even over prolonged storage.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Another application was for acoustic homing torpedoes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Two pairs of directional hydrophones were mounted on the torpedo nose, in the horizontal and vertical plane; the difference signals from the pairs were used to steer the torpedo left-right and up-down.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A countermeasure was developed: the targeted submarine discharged an effervescent chemical, and the torpedo went after the noisier fizzy decoy.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The counter-countermeasure was a torpedo with active sonar – a transducer was added to the torpedo nose, and the microphones were listening for its reflected periodic tone bursts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The transducers comprised identical rectangular crystal plates arranged to diamond-shaped areas in staggered rows.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar arrays for submarines were developed from ADP crystals.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Several crystal assemblies were arranged in a steel tube, vacuum-filled with castor oil, and sealed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The tubes then were mounted in parallel arrays.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The standard US Navy scanning sonar at the end of World War II operated at 18 kHz, using an array of ADP crystals.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Desired longer range, however, required use of lower frequencies.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The required dimensions were too big for ADP crystals, so in the early 1950s magnetostrictive and barium titanate piezoelectric systems were developed, but these had problems achieving uniform impedance characteristics, and the beam pattern suffered.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Barium titanate was then replaced with more stable lead zirconate titanate (PZT), and the frequency was lowered to 5 kHz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The US fleet used this material in the AN/SQS-23 sonar for several decades.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The SQS-23 sonar first used magnetostrictive nickel transducers, but these weighed several tons, and nickel was expensive and considered a critical material; piezoelectric transducers were therefore substituted.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The sonar was a large array of 432 individual transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] At first, the transducers were unreliable, showing mechanical and electrical failures and deteriorating soon after installation; they were also produced by several vendors, had different designs, and their characteristics were different enough to impair the array's performance.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The policy to allow repair of individual transducers was then sacrificed, and "expendable modular design", sealed non-repairable modules, was chosen instead, eliminating the problem with seals and other extraneous mechanical parts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The Imperial Japanese Navy at the onset of World War II used projectors based on quartz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] These were big and heavy, especially if designed for lower frequencies; the one for Type 91 set, operating at 9 kHz, had a diameter of 30 inches (760 mm) and was driven by an oscillator with 5 kW power and 7 kV of output amplitude.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The Type 93 projectors consisted of solid sandwiches of quartz, assembled into spherical cast iron bodies.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The Type 93 sonars were later replaced with Type 3, which followed German design and used magnetostrictive projectors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The projectors consisted of two rectangular identical independent units in a cast-iron rectangular body about 16 by 9 inches (410 mm × 230 mm).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The exposed area was half the wavelength wide and three wavelengths high.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The magnetostrictive cores were made from 4 mm stampings of nickel, and later of an iron-aluminium alloy with aluminium content between 12.7% and 12.9%.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The power was provided from a 2 kW at 3.8 kV, with polarization from a 20 V, 8 A DC source.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The passive hydrophones of the Imperial Japanese Navy were based on moving-coil design, Rochelle salt piezo transducers, and carbon microphones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Magnetostrictive transducers were pursued after World War II as an alternative to piezoelectric ones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Nickel scroll-wound ring transducers were used for high-power low-frequency operations, with size up to 13 feet (4.0 m) in diameter, probably the largest individual sonar transducers ever.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The advantage of metals is their high tensile strength and low input electrical impedance, but they have electrical losses and lower coupling coefficient than PZT, whose tensile strength can be increased by prestressing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Nonmetallic ferrites were promising for their low electrical conductivity resulting in low eddy current losses, Metglas offered high coupling coefficient, but they were inferior to PZT overall.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In the 1970s, compounds of rare earths and iron were discovered with superior magnetomechanic properties, namely the Terfenol-D alloy.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This made possible new designs, e.g. a hybrid magnetostrictive-piezoelectric transducer.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The most recent of these improved magnetostrictive materials is Galfenol.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar uses a sound transmitter (or projector) and a receiver.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When the two are in the same place it is monostatic operation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When the transmitter and receiver are separated it is bistatic operation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When more transmitters (or more receivers) are used, again spatially separated, it is multistatic operation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Most sonars are used monostatically with the same array often being used for transmission and reception.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonobuoy fields may be operated multistatically.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar creates a pulse of sound, often called a *ping*, and then listens for reflections (echo) of the pulse.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This pulse of sound is generally created electronically using a sonar projector consisting of a signal generator, power amplifier and electro-acoustic transducer/array.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A transducer is a device that can transmit and receive acoustic signals ("pings").
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A beamformer is usually employed to concentrate the acoustic power into a beam, which may be swept to cover the required search angles.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Generally, the electro-acoustic transducers are of the Tonpilz type and their design may be optimised to achieve maximum efficiency over the widest bandwidth, in order to optimise performance of the overall system.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Occasionally, the acoustic pulse may be created by other means, e.g. chemically using explosives, airguns or plasma sound sources.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To measure the distance to an object, the time from transmission of a pulse to reception is measured and converted into a range using the known speed of sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To measure the bearing, several hydrophones are used, and the set measures the relative arrival time to each, or with an array of hydrophones, by measuring the relative amplitude in beams formed through a process called beamforming.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Use of an array reduces the spatial response so that to provide wide cover multibeam systems are used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The target signal, if present, together with noise is then passed through forms of signal processing, which for simple sonars may be just energy measurement.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It is then presented to some form of decision device, that calls the output either the required signal or noise.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This decision device may be an operator with headphones or a display.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In more sophisticated sonars this function may be carried out by software.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Further processes may be carried out to classify the target and localise it, as well as measuring its velocity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The pulse may be at constant frequency or a chirp of changing frequency, to allow pulse compression on reception.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Simple sonars generally use the former with a filter wide enough to cover possible Doppler changes due to target movement, while more complex ones generally include the latter technique.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since digital processing became available pulse compression has usually been implemented using digital correlation techniques.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Military sonars often have multiple beams to provide all-round cover, while simple ones only cover a narrow arc, although the beam may be rotated, relatively slowly, by mechanical scanning.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Particularly when single frequency transmissions are used, the Doppler effect can be used to measure the radial speed of a target.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The difference in frequency between the transmitted and received signal is measured and converted into a velocity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since Doppler shifts can be introduced by either receiver or target motion, allowance has to be made for the radial speed of the searching platform.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] One useful small sonar is similar in appearance to a waterproof flashlight.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The head is pointed into the water, a button is pressed, and the device displays the distance to the target.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Another variant is a "fishfinder" that shows a small display with shoals of fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Some civilian sonars, which are not designed for stealth, approach active military sonars in capability, with three-dimensional displays of the area near the boat.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When active sonar is used to measure the distance from the transducer to the bottom, it is known as echo sounding.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Similar methods may be used looking upward for wave measurement.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar is also used to measure distance through water between two sonar transducers or a combination of a hydrophone (underwater acoustic microphone) and projector (underwater acoustic speaker).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When a hydrophone/transducer receives a specific interrogation signal it responds by transmitting a specific reply signal.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To measure distance, one transducer/projector transmits an interrogation signal and measures the time between this transmission and the receipt of the other transducer/hydrophone reply.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The time difference, scaled by the speed of sound through water and divided by two, is the distance between the two platforms.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This technique, when used with multiple transducers/hydrophones/projectors, can calculate the relative positions of static and moving objects in water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In combat situations, an active pulse can be detected by an enemy and will reveal a submarine's position at twice the maximum distance that the submarine can itself detect a contact and give clues as to the submarine's identity based on the characteristics of the outgoing ping.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] For these reasons, active sonar is not frequently used by military submarines.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A very directional, but low-efficiency, type of sonar, used by fisheries, military, and for port security, makes use of a complex nonlinear feature of water known as non-linear sonar, the virtual transducer being known as a *parametric array*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Project Artemis was an experimental research and development project in the late 1950s to mid 1960s to examine acoustic propagation and signal processing for a low-frequency active sonar system that might be used for ocean surveillance.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A secondary objective was examination of engineering problems of fixed active bottom systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The receiving array was located on the slope of Plantagnet Bank off Bermuda.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The active source array was deployed from the converted World War II tanker USNS *Mission Capistrano*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Elements of Artemis were used experimentally after the main experiment was terminated.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This is an active sonar device that receives a specific stimulus and immediately (or with a delay) retransmits the received signal or a predetermined one.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Transponders can be used to remotely activate or recover subsea equipment.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A sonar target is small relative to the sphere, centred around the emitter, on which it is located.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Therefore, the power of the reflected signal is very low, several orders of magnitude less than the original signal.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Even if the reflected signal was of the same power, the following example (using hypothetical values) shows the problem: Suppose a sonar system is capable of emitting a 10,000 W/m2 signal at 1 m, and detecting a 0.001 W/m2 signal.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] At 100 m the signal will be 1 W/m2, due to the inverse-square law.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] If the entire signal is reflected from a 10 m2 target, it will be at 0.001 W/m2 when it reaches the emitter, i.e. just detectable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] However, the original signal will remain above 0.001 W/m2 until 3000 m.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Any 10 m2 target between 100 and 3000 m using a similar or better system would be able to detect the pulse, but would not be detected by the emitter.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The detectors must be very sensitive to pick up the echoes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since the original signal is much more powerful, it can be detected many times further than twice the range of the sonar (as in the example).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar have two performance limitations: due to noise and reverberation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In general, one or other of these will dominate, so that the two effects can be initially considered separately.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] where SL is the source level, PL is the propagation loss (sometimes referred to as transmission loss), TS is the target strength, NL is the noise level, AG is the array gain of the receiving array (sometimes approximated by its directivity index) and DT is the detection threshold.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] where RL is the reverberation level, and the other factors are as before.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An upward looking sonar (ULS) is a sonar device pointed upwards looking towards the surface of the sea.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It is used for similar purposes as downward looking sonar, but has some unique applications such as measuring sea ice thickness, roughness and concentration, or measuring air entrainment from bubble plumes during rough seas.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Often it is moored on the bottom of the ocean or floats on a taut line mooring at a constant depth of perhaps 100 m.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] They may also be used by submarines, AUVs, and floats such as the Argo float.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar listens without transmitting.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It is often employed in military settings, although it is also used in science applications, *e.g.*, detecting fish for presence/absence studies in various aquatic environments – see also passive acoustics and passive radar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In the very broadest usage, this term can encompass virtually any analytical technique involving remotely generated sound, though it is usually restricted to techniques applied in an aquatic environment.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar has a wide variety of techniques for identifying the source of a detected sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] For example, U.S. vessels usually operate 60 Hertz (Hz) alternating current power systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] If transformers or generators are mounted without proper vibration insulation from the hull or become flooded, the 60 Hz sound from the windings can be emitted from the submarine or ship.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This can help to identify its nationality, as all European submarines and nearly every other nation's submarine have 50 Hz power systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Intermittent sound sources (such as a wrench being dropped), called "transients," may also be detectable to passive sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Until fairly recently, an experienced, trained operator identified signals, but now computers may do this.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar systems may have large sonic databases, but the sonar operator usually finally classifies the signals manually.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A computer system frequently uses these databases to identify classes of ships, actions (i.e. the speed of a ship, or the type of weapon released and the most effective countermeasures to employ), and even particular ships.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar on vehicles is usually severely limited because of noise generated by the vehicle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] For this reason, many submarines operate nuclear reactors that can be cooled without pumps, using silent convection, or fuel cells or batteries, which can also run silently.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Vehicles' propellers are also designed and precisely machined to emit minimal noise.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] High-speed propellers often create tiny bubbles in the water, and this cavitation has a distinct sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The sonar hydrophones may be towed behind the ship or submarine in order to reduce the effect of noise generated by the watercraft itself.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Towed units also combat the thermocline, as the unit may be towed above or below the thermocline.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The display of most passive sonars used to be a two-dimensional waterfall display.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The horizontal direction of the display is bearing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The vertical is frequency, or sometimes time.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Another display technique is to color-code frequency-time information for bearing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] More recent displays are generated by the computers, and mimic radar-type plan position indicator displays.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Unlike active sonar, only one-way propagation is involved.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Because of the different signal processing used, the minimal detectable signal-to-noise ratio will be different.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] where SL is the source level, PL is the propagation loss, NL is the noise level, AG is the array gain and DT is the detection threshold.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The detection, classification and localisation performance of a sonar depends on the environment and the receiving equipment, as well as the transmitting equipment in an active sonar or the target radiated noise in a passive sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sonar operation is affected by variations in sound speed, particularly in the vertical plane.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sound travels more slowly in fresh water than in sea water, though the difference is small.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The speed is determined by the water's bulk modulus and mass density.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The bulk modulus is affected by temperature, dissolved impurities (usually salinity), and pressure.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This empirically derived approximation equation is reasonably accurate for normal temperatures, concentrations of salinity and the range of most ocean depths.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Ocean temperature varies with depth, but at between 30 and 100 meters there is often a marked change, called the thermocline, dividing the warmer surface water from the cold, still waters that make up the rest of the ocean.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This can frustrate sonar, because a sound originating on one side of the thermocline tends to be bent, or refracted, through the thermocline.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The thermocline may be present in shallower coastal waters.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Wave action will often mix the water column and eliminate the thermocline.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Water pressure also affects sound propagation: higher pressure increases the sound speed, which causes the sound waves to refract away from the area of higher sound speed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The mathematical model of refraction is called Snell's law.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] If the sound source is deep and the conditions are right, propagation may occur in the 'deep sound channel'.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This provides extremely low propagation loss to a receiver in the channel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This is because of sound trapping in the channel with no losses at the boundaries.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Similar propagation can occur in the 'surface duct' under suitable conditions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In this case, there are reflection losses at the surface.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In shallow water propagation is generally by repeated reflection at the surface and bottom, where considerable losses can occur.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sound propagation is affected by absorption in the water itself as well as at the surface and bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This absorption depends upon frequency, with several different mechanisms in sea water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Long-range sonar uses low frequencies to minimise absorption effects.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The sea contains many sources of noise that interfere with the desired target echo or signature.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The main noise sources are waves and shipping.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The motion of the receiver through the water can also cause speed-dependent low frequency noise.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When active sonar is used, scattering occurs from small objects in the sea as well as from the bottom and surface.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This can be a major source of interference.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] For analogous reasons active sonar needs to transmit in a narrow beam to minimize scattering.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The scattering of sonar from objects (mines, pipelines, zooplankton, geological features, fish etc.) is how active sonar detects them, but this ability can be masked by strong scattering from false targets, or 'clutter'.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Where they occur (under breaking waves; in ship wakes; in gas emitted from seabed seeps and leaks etc.), gas bubbles are powerful sources of clutter, and can readily hide targets.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] TWIPS (Twin Inverted Pulse Sonar) is currently the only sonar that can overcome this clutter problem.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This is important as many recent conflicts have occurred in coastal waters, and the inability to detect whether mines are present or not present hazards and delays to military vessels, and also to aid convoys and merchant shipping trying to support the region long after the conflict has ceased.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The sound *reflection* characteristics of the target of an active sonar, such as a submarine, are known as its target strength.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A complication is that echoes are also obtained from other objects in the sea such as whales, wakes, schools of fish and rocks.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar detects the target's *radiated* noise characteristics.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The radiated spectrum comprises a continuous spectrum of noise with peaks at certain frequencies which can be used for classification.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Modern naval warfare makes extensive use of both passive and active sonar from water-borne vessels, aircraft and fixed installations.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Although active sonar was used by surface craft in World War II, submarines avoided the use of active sonar due to the potential for revealing their presence and position to enemy forces.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] However, the advent of modern signal-processing enabled the use of passive sonar as a primary means for search and detection operations.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1987 a division of Japanese company Toshiba reportedly sold machinery to the Soviet Union that allowed their submarine propeller blades to be milled so that they became radically quieter, making the newer generation of submarines more difficult to detect.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The use of active sonar by a submarine to determine bearing is extremely rare and will not necessarily give high quality bearing or range information to the submarines fire control team.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] However, use of active sonar on surface ships is very common and is used by submarines when the tactical situation dictates that it is more important to determine the position of a hostile submarine than conceal their own position.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] With surface ships, it might be assumed that the threat is already tracking the ship with satellite data as any vessel around the emitting sonar will detect the emission.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Having heard the signal, it is easy to identify the sonar equipment used (usually with its frequency) and its position (with the sound wave's energy).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar is similar to radar in that, while it allows detection of targets at a certain range, it also enables the emitter to be detected at a far greater range, which is undesirable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since active sonar reveals the presence and position of the operator, and does not allow exact classification of targets, it is used by fast (planes, helicopters) and by noisy platforms (most surface ships) but rarely by submarines.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] When active sonar is used by surface ships or submarines, it is typically activated very briefly at intermittent periods to minimize the risk of detection.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Consequently, active sonar is normally considered a backup to passive sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In aircraft, active sonar is used in the form of disposable sonobuoys that are dropped in the aircraft's patrol area or in the vicinity of possible enemy sonar contacts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Passive sonar has several advantages, most importantly that it is silent.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] If the target radiated noise level is high enough, it can have a greater range than active sonar, and allows the target to be identified.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since any motorized object makes some noise, it may in principle be detected, depending on the level of noise emitted and the ambient noise level in the area, as well as the technology used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] To simplify, passive sonar "sees" around the ship using it.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] On a submarine, nose-mounted passive sonar detects in directions of about 270°, centered on the ship's alignment, the hull-mounted array of about 160° on each side, and the towed array of a full 360°.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The invisible areas are due to the ship's own interference.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Once a signal is detected in a certain direction (which means that something makes sound in that direction, this is called broadband detection) it is possible to zoom in and analyze the signal received (narrowband analysis).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This is generally done using a Fourier transform to show the different frequencies making up the sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Since every engine makes a specific sound, it is straightforward to identify the object.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Databases of unique engine sounds are part of what is known as *acoustic intelligence* or ACINT.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Another use of passive sonar is to determine the target's trajectory.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This process is called target motion analysis (TMA), and the resultant "solution" is the target's range, course, and speed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] TMA is done by marking from which direction the sound comes at different times, and comparing the motion with that of the operator's own ship.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Changes in relative motion are analyzed using standard geometrical techniques along with some assumptions about limiting cases.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It requires high-tech electronic components.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It is generally deployed on advanced ships in the form of arrays to enhance detection.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It is also used by airplanes and helicopters, mostly to a "surprise effect", since submarines can hide under thermal layers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] If a submarine's commander believes he is alone, he may bring his boat closer to the surface and be easier to detect, or go deeper and faster, and thus make more sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Examples of sonar applications in military use are given below.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Many of the civil uses given in the following section may also be applicable to naval use.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Until recently, ship sonars were usually made with hull mounted arrays, either amidships or at the bow.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] It was soon found after their initial use that a means of reducing flow noise was required.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The first were made of canvas on a framework, then steel ones were used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Now domes are usually made of reinforced plastic or pressurized rubber.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Such sonars are primarily active in operation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An example of a conventional hull mounted sonar is the SQS-56.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Because of the problems of ship noise, towed sonars are also used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] These have the advantage of being able to be placed deeper in the water, but have limitations on their use in shallow water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] These are called towed arrays (linear) or variable depth sonars (VDS) with 2/3D arrays.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A problem is that the winches required to deploy/recover them are large and expensive.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] VDS sets are primarily active in operation, while towed arrays are passive.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An example of a modern active-passive ship towed sonar is Sonar 2087 made by Thales Underwater Systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Modern torpedoes are generally fitted with an active/passive sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This may be used to home directly on the target, but wake homing torpedoes are also used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An early example of an acoustic homer was the Mark 37 torpedo.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Torpedo countermeasures can be towed or free.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An early example was the German *Sieglinde* device while the *Bold* was a chemical device.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A widely used US device was the towed AN/SLQ-25 Nixie while the mobile submarine simulator (MOSS) was a free device.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A modern alternative to the Nixie system is the UK Royal Navy S2170 Surface Ship Torpedo Defence system.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Mines may be fitted with a sonar to detect, localize and recognize the required target.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Mine countermeasure (MCM) sonar, sometimes called "mine and obstacle avoidance sonar (MOAS)", is a specialized type of sonar used for detecting small objects.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Most MCM sonars are hull mounted but a few types are VDS design.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An example of a hull mounted MCM sonar is the Type 2193 while the SQQ-32 mine-hunting sonar and Type 2093 systems are VDS designs.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Submarines rely on sonar to a greater extent than surface ships as they cannot use radar in water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The sonar arrays may be hull mounted or towed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Information fitted on typical fits is given in *Oyashio*-class submarine and *Swiftsure*-class submarine.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Helicopters can be used for antisubmarine warfare by deploying fields of active-passive sonobuoys or can operate dipping sonar, such as the AQS-13.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Fixed wing aircraft can also deploy sonobuoys and have greater endurance and capacity to deploy them.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Processing from the sonobuoys or dipping sonar can be on the aircraft or on ship.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Dipping sonar has the advantage of being deployable to depths appropriate to daily conditions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Helicopters have also been used for mine countermeasure missions using towed sonars such as the AQS-20A.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Dedicated sonars can be fitted to ships and submarines for underwater communication.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The systems exploited the SOFAR channel, also known as the deep sound channel, where a sound speed minimum creates a waveguide in which low frequency sound travels thousands of miles.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Analysis was based on an AT&T sound spectrograph, which converted sound into a visual spectrogram representing a time–frequency analysis of sound that was developed for speech analysis and modified to analyze low-frequency underwater sounds.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] That process was Low Frequency Analysis and Recording and the equipment was termed the Low Frequency Analyzer and Recorder, both with the acronym LOFAR.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] LOFAR research was termed *Jezebel* and led to usage in air and surface systems, particularly sonobuoys using the process and sometimes using "Jezebel" in their name.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The proposed system offered such promise of long-range submarine detection that the Navy ordered immediate moves for implementation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Between installation of a test array followed by a full scale, forty element, prototype operational array in 1951 and 1958 systems were installed in the Atlantic and then the Pacific under the unclassified name *Project Caesar*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The original systems were terminated at classified shore stations designated Naval Facility (NAVFAC) explained as engaging in "ocean research" to cover their classified mission.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The system was upgraded multiple times with more advanced cable allowing the arrays to be installed in ocean basins and upgraded processing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The shore stations were eliminated in a process of consolidation and rerouting the arrays to central processing centers into the 1990s.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1985, with new mobile arrays and other systems becoming operational the collective system name was changed to Integrated Undersea Surveillance System (IUSS).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] In 1991, the mission of the system was declassified.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The year before IUSS insignia were authorized for wear.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Access was granted to some systems for scientific research.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] A similar system is believed to have been operated by the Soviet Union.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Sonar can be used to detect frogmen and other scuba divers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This can be applicable around ships or at entrances to ports.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Active sonar can also be used as a deterrent and/or disablement mechanism.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Limpet mine imaging sonar (LIMIS) is a hand-held or ROV-mounted imaging sonar designed for patrol divers (combat frogmen or clearance divers) to look for limpet mines in low visibility water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] The LUIS is another imaging sonar for use by a diver.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] Integrated navigation sonar system (INSS) is a small flashlight-shaped handheld sonar for divers that displays range.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] This is a sonar designed to detect and locate the transmissions from hostile active sonars.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p01] An example of this is the Type 2082 fitted on the British *Vanguard*-class submarines.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Fishing is an important industry that is seeing growing demand, but world catch tonnage is falling as a result of serious resource problems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The industry faces a future of continuing worldwide consolidation until a point of sustainability can be reached.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] However, the consolidation of the fishing fleets are driving increased demands for sophisticated fish finding electronics such as sensors, sounders and sonars.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Historically, fishermen have used many different techniques to find and harvest fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] However, acoustic technology has been one of the most important driving forces behind the development of the modern commercial fisheries.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Sound waves travel differently through fish than through water because a fish's air-filled swim bladder has a different density than seawater.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] This density difference allows the detection of schools of fish by using reflected sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Acoustic technology is especially well suited for underwater applications since sound travels farther and faster underwater than in air.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Today, commercial fishing vessels rely almost completely on acoustic sonar and sounders to detect fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Fishermen also use active sonar and echo sounder technology to determine water depth, bottom contour, and bottom composition.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Companies such as eSonar, Raymarine, Marport Canada, Wesmar, Furuno, Krupp, and Simrad make a variety of sonar and acoustic instruments for the deep sea commercial fishing industry.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] For example, net sensors take various underwater measurements and transmit the information back to a receiver on board a vessel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Each sensor is equipped with one or more acoustic transducers depending on its specific function.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Data is transmitted from the sensors using wireless acoustic telemetry and is received by a hull mounted hydrophone.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The analog signals are decoded and converted by a digital acoustic receiver into data which is transmitted to a bridge computer for graphical display on a high resolution monitor.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Echo sounding is a process used to determine the depth of water beneath ships and boats.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] A type of active sonar, echo sounding is the transmission of an acoustic pulse directly downwards to the seabed, measuring the time between transmission and echo return, after having hit the bottom and bouncing back to its ship of origin.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The acoustic pulse is emitted by a transducer which receives the return echo as well.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The depth measurement is calculated by multiplying the speed of sound in water (averaging 1,500 meters per second) by the time between emission and echo return.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The value of underwater acoustics to the fishing industry has led to the development of other acoustic instruments that operate in a similar fashion to echo-sounders but, because their function is slightly different from the initial model of the echo-sounder, have been given different terms.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The net sounder is an echo sounder with a transducer mounted on the headline of the net rather than on the bottom of the vessel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Nevertheless, to accommodate the distance from the transducer to the display unit, which is much greater than in a normal echo-sounder, several refinements have to be made.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The first is the cable type in which the signals are sent along a cable.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] In this case, there has to be the provision of a cable drum on which to haul, shoot and stow the cable during the different phases of the operation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The second type is the cable-less net-sounder – such as Marport's Trawl Explorer – in which the signals are sent acoustically between the net and hull mounted receiver-hydrophone on the vessel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] In this case, no cable drum is required but sophisticated electronics are needed at the transducer and receiver.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The display on a net sounder shows the distance of the net from the bottom (or the surface), rather than the depth of water as with the echo-sounder's hull-mounted transducer.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Fixed to the headline of the net, the footrope can usually be seen which gives an indication of the net performance.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Any fish passing into the net can also be seen, allowing fine adjustments to be made to catch the most fish possible.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] In other fisheries, where the amount of fish in the net is important, catch sensor transducers are mounted at various positions on the cod-end of the net.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] As the cod-end fills up these catch sensor transducers are triggered one by one and this information is transmitted acoustically to display monitors on the bridge of the vessel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The skipper can then decide when to haul the net.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Modern versions of the net sounder, using multiple element transducers, function more like a sonar than an echo sounder and show slices of the area in front of the net and not merely the vertical view that the initial net sounders used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The sonar is an echo-sounder with a directional capability that can show fish or other objects around the vessel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Small sonars have been fitted to remotely operated vehicles (ROVs) and unmanned underwater vehicles (UUVs) to allow their operation in murky conditions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] These sonars are used for looking ahead of the vehicle.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The AN/BLQ-11 Long-Term Mine Reconnaissance System is a UUV for MCM purposes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Sonars which act as beacons are fitted to aircraft to allow their location in the event of a crash in the sea.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Short and long baseline sonars may be used for caring out the location, such as LBL.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] In 2013 an inventor in the United States unveiled a "spider-sense" bodysuit, equipped with ultrasonic sensors and haptic feedback systems, which alerts the wearer of incoming threats; allowing them to respond to attackers even when blindfolded.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Detection of fish, and other marine and aquatic life, and estimation their individual sizes or total biomass using active sonar techniques.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Sound pulses reflect off any object that has a different density than the surrounding medium.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] This includes fish, or more specifically, the air-filled swim bladder on fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] These echoes provide information on fish size, location, abundance and behavior.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] This is especially effective for fish swim bladders (e.g. herring, cod, and pollock), and less useful for fish without them (e.g. sharks, mackerel, and flounder).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Data from the watercolumn is usually processed differently than seafloor or object detection data, this data type can be processed with specialized software.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] An upward looking echo sounder mounted on the bottom or on a platform may be used to make measurements of wave height and period.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] From this statistics of the surface conditions at a location can be derived.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Special short range sonars have been developed to allow measurements of water velocity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Sonars have been developed that can be used to characterise the sea bottom into, for example, mud, sand, and gravel.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Relatively simple sonars such as echo sounders can be promoted to seafloor classification systems via add-on modules, converting echo parameters into sediment type.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Different algorithms exist, but they are all based on changes in the energy or shape of the reflected sounder pings.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Advanced substrate classification analysis can be achieved using calibrated (scientific) echosounders and parametric or fuzzy-logic analysis of the acoustic data.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Side-scan sonars can be used to derive maps of seafloor topography (bathymetry) by moving the sonar across it just above the bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Low frequency sonars such as GLORIA have been used for continental shelf wide surveys while high frequency sonars are used for more detailed surveys of smaller areas.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Hull-mounted multibeam echosounders on large surface vessels produce swathes of bathymetric data in near real time.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] One example, the General Instrument "Seabeam" system, uses a projector array along the keel to ensonify the bottom with a fan beam.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Signals from a hydrophone array mounted athwartships are processed to synthesize multiple virtual fan beams crossing the projector beam at right angles.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Creating two and three-dimensional images using sonar data.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Powerful low frequency echo-sounders have been developed for providing profiles of the upper layers of the ocean bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] One of the most recent devices is Innomar's SES-2000 quattro multi-transducer parametric SBP, used for example in the Puck Bay for underwater archaeological purposes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Gas bubbles can leak from the seabed, or close to it, from multiple sources.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] These can be detected by both passive and active sonar (shown in schematic figure by yellow and red systems respectively).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Natural seeps of methane and carbon dioxide occur.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Gas pipelines can leak, and it is important to be able to detect whether leakage occurs from Carbon Capture and Storage Facilities (CCSFs; e.g. depleted oil wells into which extracted atmospheric carbon is stored).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Quantification of the amount of gas leaking is difficult, and although estimates can be made use active and passive sonar, it is important to question their accuracy because of the assumptions inherent in making such estimations from sonar data.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Various synthetic aperture sonars have been built in the laboratory and some have entered use in mine-hunting and search systems.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] An explanation of their operation is given in synthetic aperture sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Parametric sources use the non-linearity of water to generate the difference frequency between two high frequencies.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Such a projector has advantages of broad bandwidth, narrow beamwidth, and when fully developed and carefully measured it has no obvious sidelobes: see Parametric array.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Its major disadvantage is very low efficiency of only a few percent.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Westervelt summarizes the trends involved.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The use of both active and passive sonar has been proposed for various extraterrestrial environments.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] One example is Titan, where active sonar could be used to determine the depth of its hydrocarbon seas, and passive sonar could be used to detect methanefalls.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Proposals that do not take proper account of the difference between terrestrial and extraterrestrial environments could lead to erroneous measurements.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Research has shown that use of active sonar can lead to mass strandings of marine mammals.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Beaked whales, the most common casualty of the strandings, have been shown to be highly sensitive to mid-frequency active sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Other marine mammals such as the blue whale also flee from the source of the sonar, while naval activity was suggested to be the most probable cause of a mass stranding of dolphins.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The US Navy, which part-funded some of the studies, said that the findings only showed behavioural responses to sonar, not actual harm, but they "will evaluate the effectiveness of [their] marine mammal protective measures in light of new research findings".
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] A 2008 US Supreme Court ruling on the use of sonar by the US Navy noted that there had been no cases where sonar had been conclusively shown to have harmed or killed a marine mammal.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Some marine animals, such as whales and dolphins, use echolocation systems, sometimes called *biosonar* to locate predators and prey.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Research on the effects of sonar on blue whales in the Southern California Bight shows that mid-frequency sonar use disrupts the whales' feeding behavior.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] This indicates that sonar-induced disruption of feeding and displacement from high-quality prey patches could have significant and previously undocumented impacts on baleen whale foraging ecology, individual fitness and population health.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] A review of evidence on the mass strandings of beaked whale linked to naval exercises where sonar was used was published in 2019.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] It concluded that the effects of mid-frequency active sonar are strongest on Cuvier's beaked whales but vary among individuals or populations.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The review suggested the strength of response of individual animals may depend on whether they had prior exposure to sonar, and that symptoms of decompression sickness have been found in stranded whales that may be a result of such response to sonar.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] It noted that in the Canary Islands where multiple strandings had been previously reported, no more mass strandings had occurred once naval exercises during which sonar was used were banned in the area, and recommended that the ban be extended to other areas where mass strandings continue to occur.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Low frequency sonar can create a small temporary shift in the hearing threshold of some fish.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The frequencies of sonars range from infrasonic to above a megahertz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Generally, the lower frequencies have longer range, while the higher frequencies offer better resolution, and smaller size for a given directionality.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] To achieve reasonable directionality, frequencies below 1 kHz generally require large size, usually achieved as towed arrays.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Low frequency sonars are loosely defined as 1–5 kHz, albeit some navies regard 5–7 kHz also as low frequency.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Medium frequency is defined as 5–15 kHz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Another style of division considers low frequency to be under 1 kHz, and medium frequency at between 1–10 kHz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] American World War II era sonars operated at a relatively high frequency of 20–30 kHz, to achieve directionality with reasonably small transducers, with typical maximum operational range of 2,500 yd.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Postwar sonars used lower frequencies to achieve longer range; e.g.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] SQS-4 operated at 10 kHz with range up to 5,000 yd.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] SQS-26 and SQS-53 operated at 3 kHz with range up to 20,000 yd; their domes had size of approx. a 60-ft personnel boat, an upper size limit for conventional hull sonars.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Achieving larger sizes by conformal sonar array spread over the hull has not been effective so far, for lower frequencies linear or towed arrays are therefore used.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Japanese WW2 sonars operated at a range of frequencies.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The Type 91, with 30 inch quartz projector, worked at 9 kHz.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The Type 93, with smaller quartz projectors, operated at 17.5 kHz (model 5 at 16 or 19 kHz magnetostrictive) at powers between 1.7 and 2.5 kilowatts, with range of up to 6 km.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The later Type 3, with German-design magnetostrictive transducers, operated at 13, 14.5, 16, or 20 kHz (by model), using twin transducers (except model 1 which had three single ones), at 0.2 to 2.5 kilowatts.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The simple type used 14.5 kHz magnetostrictive transducers at 0.25 kW, driven by capacitive discharge instead of oscillators, with range up to 2.5 km.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] The sonar's resolution is angular; objects further apart are imaged with lower resolutions than nearby ones.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Another source lists ranges and resolutions vs frequencies for sidescan sonars.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] 30 kHz provides low resolution with range of 1000–6,000 m, 100 kHz gives medium resolution at 500–1,000 m, 300 kHz gives high resolution at 150–500 m, and 600 kHz gives high resolution at 75–150 m.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Longer range sonars are more adversely affected by nonhomogenities of water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/sonar-p02] Some environments, typically shallow waters near the coasts, have complicated terrain with many features; higher frequencies become necessary there.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasound can be used for measuring wind speed and direction (anemometer), tank or channel fluid level, and speed through air or water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] For measuring speed or direction, a device uses multiple detectors and calculates the speed from the relative distances to particulates in the air or water.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] To measure tank or channel liquid level, and also sea level (tide gauge), the sensor measures the distance (ranging) to the surface of the fluid.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Further applications include: humidifiers, sonar, medical ultrasonography, burglar alarms and non-destructive testing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Systems typically use a transducer that generates sound waves in the ultrasonic range, above 20 kHz, by turning electrical energy into sound, then upon receiving the echo turn the sound waves into electrical energy which can be measured and displayed.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] This technology, as well, can detect approaching objects and track their positions.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasound can also be used to make point-to-point distance measurements by transmitting and receiving discrete bursts of ultrasound between transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] This technique is known as sonomicrometry, where the transit-time of the ultrasound signal is measured electronically (ie digitally) and converted mathematically to the distance between transducers assuming the speed of sound of the medium between the transducers is known.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] This method can be very precise in terms of temporal and spatial resolution because the time-of-flight measurement can be derived from tracking the same incident (received) waveform either by reference level or zero crossing.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] This enables the measurement resolution to far exceed the wavelength of the sound frequency generated by the transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic transducers convert alternating current (AC) into ultrasound and vice versa.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The transducers typically use piezoelectric transducers or capacitive transducers to generate or receive ultrasound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Piezoelectric crystals are able to change their sizes and shapes in response to voltage being applied.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] On the other hand, capacitive transducers use electrostatic fields between a conductive diaphragm and a backing plate.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The beam pattern of a transducer can be determined by the active transducer area and shape, the ultrasound wavelength, and the sound velocity of the propagation medium.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The diagrams show the sound fields of an unfocused and a focusing ultrasonic transducer in water, plainly at differing energy levels.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Since piezoelectric materials generate a voltage when force is applied to them, they can also work as ultrasonic detectors.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Some systems use separate transmitters and receivers, while others combine both functions into a single piezoelectric transceiver.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasound transmitters can also use non-piezoelectric principles such as magnetostriction.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Materials with this property change size slightly when exposed to a magnetic field and make practical transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] A capacitor ("condenser") microphone has a thin diaphragm that responds to ultrasound waves.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Changes in the electric field between the diaphragm and a closely spaced backing plate convert sound signals to electric currents, which can be amplified.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The diaphragm (or membrane) principle is also used in the relatively new micro-machined ultrasonic transducers (MUTs).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] These devices are fabricated using silicon micro-machining technology (MEMS technology), which is particularly useful for the fabrication of transducer arrays.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The vibration of the diaphragm may be measured or induced electronically using the capacitance between the diaphragm and a closely spaced backing plate (CMUT), or by adding a thin layer of piezo-electric material on the diaphragm (PMUT).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Alternatively, recent research showed that the vibration of the diaphragm may be measured by a tiny optical ring resonator integrated inside the diaphragm (OMUS).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic transducers can also be used for acoustic levitation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] It involves transmitting acoustic waves into water and recording the time interval between emission and return of a pulse; the resulting time of flight, along with knowledge of the speed of sound in water, allows determining the distance between sonar and target.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] This information is then typically used for navigation purposes or in order to obtain depths for charting purposes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Echo sounding is effectively a special purpose application of sonar used to locate the bottom.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Since a traditional pre-SI unit of water depth was the fathom, an instrument used for determining water depth is sometimes called a *fathometer*.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The first practical fathometer was invented by Herbert Grove Dorsey and patented in 1928.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Medical ultrasonic transducers (probes) come in a variety of different shapes and sizes for use in making cross-sectional images of various parts of the body.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] The transducer may be used in contact with the skin, as in fetal ultrasound imaging, or inserted into a body opening such as the rectum or vagina.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Clinicians who perform ultrasound-guided procedures often use a probe positioning system to hold the ultrasonic transducer.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Compared to other medical imaging modalities, ultrasound has several advantages.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] It provides images in real-time, is portable, and can consequently be brought to the bedside.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] It is substantially lower in cost than other imaging strategies and does not use harmful ionizing radiation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Drawbacks include various limits on its field of view, the need for patient cooperation, dependence on patient physique, difficulty imaging structures obscured by bone, air or gases, and the necessity of a skilled operator, usually with professional training.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Owing to these drawbacks, novel wearable ultrasound implementations are gaining popularity.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] These miniature devices continuously monitor vitals and alert at the emergence of early signs of abnormality.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic sensors can detect the movement of targets and measure the distance to them in many automated factories and process plants.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Sensors can have an on or off digital output for detecting the movement of objects, or an analog output proportional to distance.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] They can sense the edge of the material as part of a web guiding system.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic sensors are widely used in cars as parking sensors to aid the driver in reversing into parking spaces.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] They are being tested for a number of other automotive uses including ultrasonic people detection and assisting in autonomous UAV navigation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Because ultrasonic sensors use sound rather than light for detection, they work in applications where photoelectric sensors may not.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonics is a great solution for clear object detection and for liquid level measurement, applications that photoelectrics struggle with because of target translucence.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] As well, target color or reflectivity do not affect ultrasonic sensors, which can operate reliably in high-glare environments.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Passive ultrasonic sensors may be used to detect high-pressure gas or liquid leaks, or other hazardous conditions that generate ultrasonic sound.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] In these devices, ultrasound from the transducer (microphone) is converted down to the human hearing range (Audible Sound = 20 Hz to 20 kHz).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] High-power ultrasonic emitters are used in commercially available ultrasonic cleaning devices.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] An ultrasonic transducer is affixed to a stainless steel pan which is filled with a solvent (frequently water or isopropanol).
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] An electrical square wave feeds the transducer, creating sound in the solvent strong enough to cause cavitation.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic technology has been used for multiple cleaning purposes.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] One of which that been gaining a decent amount of traction in the past decade is ultrasonic gun cleaning.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] In ultrasonic welding and ultrasonic wire bonding, plastics and metals are joining using vibrations created by power ultrasonic transducers.
[src:ultrasonic-sensors/ultrasonic-transducer] Ultrasonic testing is also widely used in metallurgy and engineering to evaluate corrosion, welds, and material defects using different types of scans.
